  <p><strong>You've decluttered, painted the fence, and booked the photographer. But if you have a fireplace or wood heater, there's one thing that catches out sellers — and it shows up in the building inspection report.</strong></p>

  <p>A dirty, unserviced chimney is one of the most common maintenance issues flagged in pre-sale building inspections. Depending on how it's reported, it can trigger price renegotiations, give buyers cold feet, or simply reduce your property's appeal to the buyers who actually use their fireplace. Here's what to do about it before your home hits the market.</p>

  <h2>Why Building Inspectors Flag Fireplaces and Chimneys</h2>

  <p>Building inspectors are required to assess every accessible part of the property — including fireplaces, wood heaters and chimneys. A standard inspection will note the visible condition of the firebox, any obvious soot or creosote buildup, the state of the chimney cap and flashing, and any structural concerns with the chimney itself.</p>

  <p>An unserviced fireplace with heavy soot buildup, a bird nest in the flue, or visible creosote deposits will be noted in the report. The language used varies — "significant buildup present", "professional cleaning recommended", "evidence of long-term neglect" — but the effect is the same. The buyer sees it, their conveyancer sees it, and suddenly your fireplace goes from a selling feature to a negotiating point.</p>

  <p>In Melbourne's inner and middle suburbs — where Victorian, Edwardian and period homes with original fireplaces are common — buyers are often specifically looking for working, well-maintained fireplaces. A clean chimney and serviced flue is evidence the property has been looked after. A neglected one is the opposite.</p>

  <h2>What a Chimney Clean Before Sale Actually Does</h2>

  <p>A professional chimney clean before you list removes the creosote and soot buildup, clears any blockages, and leaves the system in a state that presents well during inspection. It takes around 45–75 minutes, costs $220 for a flue and wood heater or $320 for a masonry brick chimney, and produces a clean firebox that photographs well and reads positively in an inspection report.</p>

  <p>More practically: it removes any grounds for the inspector to flag the fireplace as a maintenance issue. A freshly cleaned chimney with no blockages or significant buildup will typically be noted as serviceable — which is exactly what you want.</p>

