  <h2>The Timing Question — When to Book</h2>

  <p>Ideally, book the chimney clean two to four weeks before the property goes live. This gives you enough time to have any structural issues (cracked crown, damaged cap, deteriorating mortar) assessed and addressed before the inspection takes place, rather than scrambling after the report comes back.</p>

  <p>If the home is already on the market and you've just received an inspection report flagging the chimney, you can still get it cleaned quickly — most jobs can be scheduled within a week. A receipt for the completed clean can then be provided to the buyer as evidence the issue has been addressed.</p>

  <h2>What Buyers Actually Look For</h2>

  <p>Buyers who are interested in a property with a fireplace or wood heater typically want to know three things: does it work, has it been maintained, and is it safe to use. A clean, recently serviced chimney answers all three. It signals that the current owners used and cared for the fireplace rather than leaving it as a decorative feature that might be full of nests and ten years of creosote.</p>

  <p>In the current Melbourne property market, a working, well-maintained fireplace is a genuine selling point — particularly for properties in the inner suburbs and outer hilly areas where wood heating is used regularly. Presenting the fireplace at its best, with evidence of recent servicing, is a low-cost way to protect that value.</p>

  <h2>Heritage Properties and Period Fireplaces</h2>

  <p>For heritage properties — Victorian terraces, Edwardian villas, Federation bungalows — the original fireplace is often a significant feature that buyers are paying a premium for. These systems require particular care: narrow flue dimensions, lime mortar, original brick liners. A heritage fireplace that's been maintained and cleaned reads very differently in an inspection than one that shows obvious long-term neglect.</p>

  <p>If your heritage fireplace hasn't been cleaned in several years, it's worth doing before sale — both for the inspection and for the photos. A clean, soot-free firebox with a clear opening is a far better visual than a grimy firebox ringed with old ash and creosote staining.</p>

  <h2>Quick Pre-Sale Chimney Checklist</h2>

  <p><strong>Book a professional clean.</strong> Get the flue and firebox cleaned before the inspection. This takes the chimney off the list of issues for the inspector to flag.</p>

  <p><strong>Check the chimney cap is present and intact.</strong> A missing or damaged cap will be noted in the inspection. Caps are inexpensive to replace if needed.</p>

  <p><strong>Clear the firebox of ash and debris.</strong> Done as part of the professional clean — but worth noting if you're doing a DIY cleanup beforehand.</p>

  <p><strong>Check the damper opens and closes.</strong> If your fireplace has a damper, it should operate freely. A seized damper will be flagged.</p>

  <p><strong>Keep the service receipt.</strong> After the clean, you'll receive confirmation. Keep this as documentation you can provide to buyers or their solicitor if the chimney is raised during negotiations.</p>

  <p>A chimney clean before sale is one of the best-value pre-sale maintenance jobs available — a couple of hundred dollars to remove a potential negotiation point and present the property's fireplace at its best. It takes less than an hour and the difference in how the inspection report reads can be significant.</p>
